data.content:
Your test works but uses generic `Assert.IsTrue` everywhere, which gives poor failure messages (just "expected True, got False"). MSTest 3.x+ has specialized collection assertions:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.IsNotEmpty(users);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive));
    Assert.HasCount(3, users);
    Assert.Contains(users.SingleOrDefault(u => u.Role == "Admin"), users);
}
```

**Key replacements:**

| Your code | Better alternative | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)` | `Assert.IsNotEmpty(users)` | Failure says "collection was empty" |
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.HasCount(3, users)` | Failure says "expected 3, found N" |
| `Single()` + `Assert.IsTrue(x != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(...)` | Clearer intent; but `Single()` already throws if missing |

The `users.All(u => u.IsActive)` check is fine — there's no built-in "assert all match predicate" in MSTest, so `Assert.IsTrue` is appropriate there.

Also consider **sealing** your test class (`public sealed class ...`) for performance, per MSTest best practices.
